Bondage Escape Challenge

That strict and tight embrace that one struggles against and maybe, just maybe, breaks triumphantly free of, or, having failed, accepts their restrained fate. Titillating times indeed. Bondage is an exacting taskmaster that can not be bribed. There is no confusion, no shades of gray. Bondage is black and white. It either is, or it is not.

Is it any wonder that people love the experience and surrender to its sensation? Once one fully leans into bondage, how long you can take it or how strict it can be often becomes a fascinating thought. Some people start fantasizing about overnight bondage or weekend-long bondage, curious about exactly what they can take.

Today’s column comes courtesy of a professional martial artist who wants to put his skills to the ultimate test—can he escape from his protégé, one that he has spent almost a year training? Can he be the Harry Houdini he believes himself to be? Or will he end up with a dislocated shoulder? Let’s find out!

“I am an experienced use of force instructor and I do it for a living. This means I train so called close-quarters-battle, use of small arms, use of handcuffs etc. About one year ago I met a woman who wanted to receive training on use of handcuffs and restraining. She is a professional dominatrix and her goal is to be able to restrain a person in the most intense and effective but safe manner. We have been training together for around 10 months now.

Now we have a sort of crazy idea–a final exam of sorts, meaning she would restrain me for one weekend and I would use any means there is to try and escape. This time I would be a real prisoner if I can’t get free. I have considered my escape-measures, hiding a handcuff key etc, etc. I would love to know your opinion: Do you think the escape will generally be possible (during the night etc.) and if not, how should I prepare myself for a weekend of imprisonment? I figured you would be the person to ask.”–Kept Extremely Yoked

https://www.raindegrey.com/bondage-escape-challenge/

Are relationships over? Is romance no more? In this digital age, where we are wired into the online experience and connections are increasingly made over electrons as opposed to in person, where does that leave the human connection? The past is like a shadow—it can shrink or it can loom large, but it will never disappear entirely. Sometimes the past is a good thing, filled with cherished memories, but other times the shadow it casts is so heavy it affects our present. What does one do when their past is traumatic enough to cause panic attacks? How does one go about getting on top of such a thing?

Today’s column comes courtesy of a reader who is seeking a fresh start and new experiences but keeps getting ambushed by anxiety severe enough that they can’t breathe. Is there a way to be left breathless by epic threesomes, or will memories of the past always come knocking at the exact wrong time? SWING is looking for answers and the DT advice column has some! Buckle up, it is time to put trauma behind us and create new patterns.

This place no longer exists. This is a captured moment in time, but the location is no more.

While on a hike, I found an an abandoned and rumbling greenhouse with stunning light coming through the broken windows. Something about the angle of the location and the leaves turned the sunlight into this beautiful honey glow.

After finding the ruins, I immediately went and shot there the next day. I didn't run out of ideas or concepts and I went to do another round on the second day, but when I got there, kit bag in hand, the greenhouse was no more--it had been leveled. There was just upturned soil and lumber scraps left. There probably is an apartment complex being built there now. Nothing lasts forever.

When you are a celebrity, everybody wants to discuss you. They want to talk about any encounter they had with you, what you were like, your every move is something to be dissected

And that isn't what this is. This is a tribute to someone who, yes, happens to be a celebrity, but was also one of the kindest and most humble people I have ever run into. And when I say "was" that is because today I found out that they passed away unexpectedly. It's the unexpected part that I am struggling so hard with. Yes, Lance Reddick was 60, but he was the most in shape 60 year old I had ever seen

It's the randomness of it that seems so unfair. Why is it that some people can utterly abuse their bodies, eat junk, not exercise, drink, smoke, do drugs and they keep on ticking year after year, and others can appear to do everything right and still be suddenly swept off the game board in the blink of an eye?? No management to file a complaint with, no takebacksies, that's all she wrote and DONE

The yardstick I go by is the "party rule". If I met you at a party, would I want to have a conversation with you? Would I want to get to know you better? Would I want to hang out with you? Would I feel relaxed and comfortable in your company?

If you use the party rule, and use it honestly, you just might find out that even some of your family members don't qualify. I certainly have some family members that I wouldn't want to sit next to at a party and have a conversation with for any extended period of time

It was around 5 years ago that Lance started following me on Twitter and began DMing me. I knew who he was, because, well, celebrity, but this isn't a tawdy expose of some married celebrity sliding into the DMs of someone like me

No, the reason he began messaging me was to tell me that my education and advice column was helpful for him and to encourage me to keep it up. Who does something like that??

#Lance Reddick, that's who

The legs. I has em. All of them.

When I was younger, I used to be teased severely about how skinny my legs are.

"How come your legs don't break when you walk?"

"Wow you really got some chicken legs, huh?"

"Don't worry dear, I had an ED when I was your age too. It'll pass."

Etc etc...

I spent years covering up my legs, acutely self-conscious of how thin they are. One day I decided to stop caring about my chicken legs. This is the body I have. I don't get to trade it in for a different model. Learning some acceptance of the meat sack you have goes a long way. These days I'm not afraid to wear a skirt or a dress and I don't hide behind baggy pants all of the time.
